[normal]W
[normal]e have 
[normal]some
[normal] concerns 
[normal]that
[normal] the issue of 
[normal]biomass 
[normal]sustainability
[normal] has been over simplified by campaigners and the media in recent 
[normal]months
[normal]. 
[normal]Biomass has several uses; generating heat, providing power in the form of electricity generation and as a fuel for transport. In discussing sustainability concerns there is a tendency to refer to all of these uses collectively without looking at th
[normal]e relative merits of each type of use. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3 
[normal]Biomass burned to produce heat is 85% efficient compared to generating electricity by burning pure biomass which is only 30-35% efficient
[normal]1
[normal]. 
[normal]The level of support provided to generate electricity from biomass is o
[normal]ut of proportion compared to the level of support for heat when the scale of inefficiency is taken into consideration.
[normal] For example, suppliers receive 1.5ROCs/MWH 
[normal]for
[normal] biomass 
[normal]electricity;
[normal] 
[normal]ROCs currently trade on average
[normal] at
[normal] 
[normal]£43
[normal],
[normal] this equates to £6
[normal]5
[normal]/MWH 
[normal]plus the price for the electricity. However, a 
[normal]1MW biomass boiler under the commercial RHI currently receives
[normal] 
[normal]1p/kWh which equates to just £10/MWH. 
[normal] 
[normal]1.
[normal]4
[normal] 
[normal]Second
[normal]ly
[normal], the use of biomass to generate heat is the most deployed technology under the non-domestic 
[normal]RHI scheme. This
[normal], along with widespread uptake in other European markets
[normal] demonstrates that biomass is currently one of the most desirable 
[normal]renewable and low carbon technologies for
[normal] consumers. The degression of the medium biomass tariff
[normal] (commercial systems b
[normal]etween 200kW and 1MW heating capacity)
[normal] under the budget management mechanism for the RHI is a serious issue. 
[normal]Whilst having a range of renewable technologies is desirable, attempting to create an equal market without reviewing current market desirability of
[normal] technologies is not in line with meeting renewables targets.
[normal] 
[normal]CPL was relieved that in the latest RHI quarterly forecast statement to 31 July 2013, no
[normal] further
[normal] degression will take place
[normal] this 
[normal]a
[normal]utumn
[normal]. However, medium biomass did exceed its trigger and the o
[normal]verall trigger was close to being met. Medium biomass only avoided 
[normal]further 
[normal]degression because this o
[normal]verall spend was a mere £800,000 below the trigger point of 
[normal]£60.1 million – despite the fact that DECC are way below required deployment levels to achieve 
[normal]renewable heat ambitions
[normal]. CPL remains concerns by how narrowly 
[normal]these triggers were missed;
[normal] medium biomass
[normal] is
[normal] on the brink of anot
[normal]her degression that could
[normal] flatten the market 
[normal]and
[normal] damage the chances of meeting renewables targets. 
