[normal]1.
[normal]5
[normal] 
[normal]We have 
[normal]some concern
[normal] over the pace of decarbonisation of heating and call upon the Committee to play particular attention to DECC’s work in the following areas:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The tariff bands for the non-domestic RHI which are causing widespread market distortion. CPL is seeing clustering
[normal] of systems at tariff boundaries (e.g. at 975/995kWh) and evidence of under specification in order to gain from the medium tariff band. This band being preferred due to the inadequate rate of return for larger installations. To resolve this issue, a more i
[normal]ntelligent tariff system is required – perhaps with a greater number of tariff bands.
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The budget management mechanism and t
[normal]he early degression of the medium biomass tariff 
[normal]which 
[normal]jeopardises achievement of renewable heat ambitions. Whilst a budget 
[normal]managemen
[normal]t tool 
[normal]is 
[normal]necessary
[normal] DECC should be enabled to apply discretion in scenarios such as 
[normal]this
[normal], where the market for the m
[normal]ost deployed technology
[normal] is 
[normal]now 
[normal]facing restrictions.
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A simple change to the RHI budget mechanism that would significantly reduce the prospect
[normal] of premature tariff degression would be to merge some of the set-aside budgets for individual tariff bands. Instead of separate budgets for small, medium and large biomass, DECC should instead have one simple consolidated budget.
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The support for biomass u
[normal]sed for heat should 
[normal]recognise incentives available for less efficient uses elsewhere and seek to encourage most efficient use of resources.
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sustainability standards for biomass for heating are in place under the RHI and should continue to be set at least a
[normal]s high as those set out for biomass at a European level. 
[normal]Standards should be reviewed on a regular basis.
[normal]2[bold].[bold] About CPL[bold] Industries[bold]2.1 
[normal]CPL Renewables is a leading specialist in wood pellet heating solutions for commercial and public sector organisations. 
[normal]CPL Renewables is an important arm of CPL Industries, Europe’s largest manufacturer and distributor of smokeless solid fuels. Operating since 1955, with over 500 employees, the company has invested substantially in diversification over the past few years w
[normal]ith a focus on renewable products.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3. Response to Questions [bold]3.[bold]1[bold] Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?[bold]3.
[normal]2
[normal] A number of policy measures have been introduced to incentivise energy efficiency improvements to reduce the 
[normal]demand for heat. These include the Green Deal and ECO with minimum energy performance an entry requirement for the domestic RHI.
[normal]3.
[normal]3
[normal] 
[normal]It should be noted that there is a limit to which heat demand can be reduced through energy efficiency in much of the UK’s 
[normal]building stock. Many older properties would require substantial and un-economic (even with Green Deal Finance) improvements to make a meaningful reduction in heat demand. In other circumstances, such as with listed buildings and in natural conservation are
[normal]as, many demand reducing measures will be unsuitable.
[normal]3.
[normal]4
[normal] 
[normal]It therefore makes sense to target low carbon and renewable heating solutions at those buildings which are using the most harmful fuels (off the gas grid) and 
[normal]for which it will be 
[normal]hardest to reduce 
[normal]demand. The associated ‘’bang for buck’’ in applying a renewable system in such circumstances will be much higher compared to a building where demand can be substantially reduced through efficiency and where the primary heating fuel is gas.
[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]What progress i
[normal]s the government making on reducing the demand for heat?
[normal]3.
[normal]6
[normal] The latest Heat Strategy document published in April 2013
[normal]2
[normal] sets out the government’s plans to meet the heat challenge in industrial heat, networked heat, heat in buildings, grids and infrastructu
[normal]re. 
[normal]3.7
[normal] [bold]CPL welcomes many of the proposals in the Heat Strategy[bold] including evidence of actions to support the launch of the domestic Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI). After a long wait for the domestic RHI scheme to be finalised (which came after the Heat Strategy was published), actions to demonstrate the government’s c
[normal]ommitment are important. 
[normal]3.
[normal]8 
[normal]The evidence annex to the 
[normal]Heat Strategy
[normal] provides two cost-optimisation scenarios models (RESOM and ESME). 
[normal]CPL is concerned 
[normal]that 
[normal]neither[bold] model shows particularly high deployment of biomass heating in 2050[bold]. This also appears con
[normal]tradictory to efforts to promote biomass through the RHI.
[normal]3.
[normal]9
[normal] The basis of a limited role for biomass in DECC’s longer term scenarios is unclear and may be due to limitations in scenario models. 
[normal]However, i
[normal]f the DECC models assume a steady-state (i.e. no fu
[normal]ture improvements) for biomass heating technology we would argue that this is unlikely to be the case.
[normal]3.
[normal]10
[normal] [bold]Biomass heating is one of the most efficient methods of producing renewable energy. There are substantial opportunities to improve the way biomass [bold]is utilised in heating within the UK[bold], through more efficient heating systems, cost reduction in manufacture and installation, alternative feedstocks and process innovations such as torrefaction. 
[normal]3.11 
[normal]Torrefaction
[normal] is the thermochemical treatment of biomass
[normal] at 200 to 320C, carried out under atmospheric pressure and in the absence of oxygen. Torrefied pellets can be produced from a wide range of biomass feedstocks and 
[normal]t
[normal]he process removes 
[normal]water and other substances leaving
[normal] a solid material which can be densifi
[normal]ed into briquettes or pellets. 
[normal]The main advantage of this process is that each torrefied pellet could contain twice the energy as those pellets available today; this reduces transportation and storage costs. 
[normal]The 
[normal]implementation of the RHI presents a medium 
[normal]term commercial opportunity for existing technologies and users. However, the Heat Strategy illustrates that 
[normal]more support for the biomass industry is required to ensure it can fulfil its important role [bold]in developing new innovative technologies[bold].[bold]3.1
[normal]2
[normal] To pro
[normal]vide more adequate support
[normal],
[normal] improvements must be made to tariff levels under the RHI. It should be noted that evidence from banks and other internal investors shows that 
[normal]the 
[normal]threshold for lending to new projects in most circumstances is a Return on Capital
[normal] Expenditure (RoCE) of 15%
[normal] or
[normal] higher. The DECC methodology uses a Rate of Return (RoR) set at just 12% which is less well recognised in the marketplace. In addition, a review of the budget management mechanism should be carried out to remove any overzealou
[normal]s
[normal] or premature
[normal] degression of tariff rates.  
[normal]3.1
[normal]3
[normal] [bold]Under the non-domestic RHI the current biomass tariffs do not provide adequate support for the technology to be deployed correctly[bold]. Clustering of installations around the tariff boundaries is evidence that 
[normal]installations are being underspecified (e.g. at 975/995kWh) to fall into the medium biomass tariff. CPL has seen instances where these underspecified systems must continue to rely on an existing fossil fuel boiler system. Had the &gt;1MW tariff provided an ad
[normal]equate rate of return then a correctly sized installation would have enabled the fossil fuel system to be completely removed.
[normal] 
[normal]3.1
[normal]4
[normal] 
[normal]Furthermore, 
[normal]the design of the budget management mechanism resulted in degression of the medium scale biomass tariff when th[bold]is is the only technology currently performing strongly.[bold] CPL is concerned that further degression will result in medium biomass installations, particularly at the lower end of the tariff boundaries
[normal],
[normal] becoming completely unviable.
[normal] CPL fears that this would f
[normal]latten
[normal] the market and severely damag
[normal]e
[normal] progress towards meeting the UK renewables targets.
[normal] 
[normal]A simple change to the RHI budget mechanism that would significantly reduce the prospect of premature tariff degression would be to merge some of the set-aside budget
[normal]s for individual tariff bands. Instead of separate budgets for small, medium and large biomass, DECC should instead have one simple consolidated budget.
[normal]3.1
[normal]5
[normal] Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives. What 
[normal]should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture?
[normal]3.1
[normal]6
[normal] DECC provides sustainability requirements for biomass including GHG requirements and in addition there are specific sustainability requirements being im
[normal]plemented under the RHI. An online tool - the UK 
[normal]Biomass &amp; Biogas Carbon Calculator
[normal] is provided by OFGEM to enable generators and others to 
[normal]assess the emissions associated with biomass electricity and heat generation. The tool takes into account the emissions across the bio-energy lifecycle from cultivation of biomass to processing and transport. The calculator should be 
[normal]reviewed on a regular 
[normal]basis to ensure the process takes into account the most up-to-date information available on the bio-energy lifecycle.
[normal]3.1
[normal]7
[normal] 
