[normal]e supply chain include:
[normal]CPL has a robust understand of sustainability issues and fully complies with each of these additional actions.
[normal]3.1
[normal]8
[normal] There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?
[normal]3.1
[normal]9
[normal] 
[normal]Under the RHI, sustainability regulations for biomass are to be laid by 
[normal]the 
[normal]end of 2013 and compliance demonstrated by April 2014. RHI recipients must provide evidence of performance; including 60% GHG savings against EU fossil fuel heat average
[normal],
[normal] and meet 
[normal]specific land use criteria. Alternatively, RHI recipients are permitted to source fuel from ‘approved supplier’ lists.
[normal]3.
[normal]20
[normal] [bold]CPL supports the introduction of biomass sustainability regulations but is concerned about confusion between the use of biomass to g[bold]enerate electricity, transport fuel and heat. [bold]Biomass for heating and combined heat power is the most effective use of biomass
[normal]. Generally speaking, using bioenergy for heat and power is more efficient in reducing GHG compared to using bioenergy for transpo
[normal]rt fuel. Indeed, burning pure biomass to produce heat is 85% efficient; generating electricity by burning the same material is only approximately 30-35% efficient
[normal]1
[normal]. 
[normal]3.2
[normal]1
[normal] The below chart (adapted from ‘The Carbon Balance of Woodfuel’, Northern Woodheat, 20
[normal]10) compares the estimated ‘carbon balance’ of a range of different woodfuels and compares them with the carbon balance of fossil fuels conventionally used for heating. The CO2 emissions associated with the use of wood as a fuel were calculated considering
[normal] every step in the process including planting, harvesting, transportation of timber, processing, transportation of processed fuel and finally the use of the wood as fuel. Woodfuels produce a relatively low amount of CO2 even where they are imported.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]2
[normal]2
[normal] 
[normal]Sustainability standards 
[normal]for biomass in the UK should reflect the desire to encourage use in its most efficient application i.e. heat.  This may mean that higher sustainability standards are required for less efficient uses such as power generation; such
[normal] as the 
[normal]70% 
[normal]GHG savings
[normal] compared to fossil fuel alternatives
[normal] recently announced to
[normal] ensure the sustainability of wood-fuel used to create energy.
[normal] [bold]3.2
[normal]3
[normal] Furthermore, a[bold]ny regulation should be in line with requirements being developed at an EU level and provid[bold]e a balance between ensuring compliance [bold]whilst not deterring investment[bold]. As the biomass market expands there will be increased competition to provide cheaper sources of biofuels, whether from within the EU or the rest of the world. R
[normal]obust r
[normal]egulations shoul
[normal]d 
[normal]prevent the use of non-sustainable sources whilst promoting a fair price for approved sources.
[normal]3.2
[normal]4
[normal] What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?
[normal]3.2
[normal]5
[normal] 
[normal]Local 
[normal]environmental pollution is potentially a big issue for the low carbon heating sector. The current application of air quality rules in planning means that companies deploying these technolog
[normal]ies 
[normal]must navigate a patchwork of different standards and requiremen
[normal]ts across the country. It makes sense to have rules on air 
[normal]quality;
[normal] however efforts to promote a national approach would be 
[normal]beneficial.
[normal]3.2
[normal]6
[normal] 
[normal]As an example, biomass boilers installed under the RHI will soon be subject to emissions constraints for NOx and Pa
[normal]rticulates. However, biomass boiler
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]not installed
[normal] 
[normal]under the RHI 
[normal]will not be subject to 
[normal]the 
[normal]same constraints. It is logical to develop consistent requirements as part of the Clean Air Act and Air Quality Regulations.
[normal] A review of the Clean Air Act is underw
[normal]ay this year.
[normal] CPL strongly supports the maintenance and development of the Clean Air Act.
[normal]3.2
[normal]7
[normal] 
[normal]Consideration should also be 
[normal]given to
[normal] the type of heating system that is being replaced with a renewable source. 
[normal]W
[normal]here 
[normal]a replacement
[normal] technology is ‘no worse’ in terms of air pollution 
[normal]than the existing system but provides considerable improvements in relation to CO2 emissions, this should be taken in consideration. This in order to avoid a scenario where older inefficient systems are n
[normal]ot being replaced because the air quality standards are too high. Ideally, CPL would advise following the same route as the Republic of Ireland and becoming entirely smokeless as the best way to tackle the issue of air
[normal] 
[normal]pollution.
[normal] Restrictions on the burnin
[normal]g of specified solid fuels would be more effective than placing restrictions on more efficient heating systems, especially where the air pollution is no worse.
[normal]3.2
[normal]8
[normal] 
[normal]In addition,
[normal] if it is designed and implemented correctly,
[normal] the European EcoDe
[normal]sign Directive 
[normal]has the potential to
[normal] solve many of the emissions problems in the domestic sector by providing a framework of requirements to reduce emissions.
